\begin_layout Standard
Cayley's work spreads over a very wide range of topics, predominantly in
 the broad fields of algebra and geometry.
 He was one of the creators of the theory of algebraic invariants.
 This elaborate edifice, now almost completely forgotten, reigned supreme
 during the last quarter of the 19th century, and was the ``modem higher
 algebra'' of the day.
 His 
\emph on
Collected Mathematical Papers
\emph default
 were published by Cambridge University Press in thirteen volumes from 1889
 to 1897 and contain 966 items ranging from very short notes to lengthy
 memoirs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On November 2, 1853 Cayley dashed off two manuscripts to the 
\emph on
Philosophical Magazine
\emph default
; one was published before the year was out, while the other appeared in
 the first issue of the 
\emph on
Magazine
\emph default
 in 1854.
 The first of these is called
