, ``On a property of the caustic by refraction of the circle''.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\emph on
caustic
\emph default
 is a curve that is always tangent to rays of light that proceed from a
 point to be reflected (or refracted) at a given surface.
 Readers familiar with envelopes will recognize this description of a caustic
 as the envelope of the reflected (or refracted) rays.
 One common way to compute caustics was to use an intermediate curve, the
 
\emph on
secondary caustic
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
orthotomic
\emph default
 curve, which consists of the reflections of the source point across all
 lines tangent to the reflecting surface.
 The caustic is the evolute of the secondary caustic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
St.
 Laurent, who earlier showed that ``in certain cases the caustic by refraction
 of a circle is identical with the caustic of reflexion of a circle (the
 reflecting circle and radiant point being, of course, properlyc hosen).''
 Cayley proposes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
to demonstrate the more general theorem, that the same caustic by refraction
 of a circle may be considered as arising from 
\emph on
six
\emph default
 different systems of a radiant point, circle, and index of refraction.
 The demonstration is obtained by means of the secondary caustic, which
 is (as is well known) an oval of Descartes.
 Such oval has three foci, any one of which may be taken for the radiant
 point: whichever be selected, there can always be found two corresponding
 circles and indices of refraction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cayley derives the equation of the secondary caustic, which contains three
 parameters: the abscissa 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 of the radiant point, the radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 of the refracting circle, and the index 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 of refraction, and puts it in several equivalent forms of which one is
 as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\left(\xi,r,\mu\right)=0
\]

\end_inset

where (we have changed the notation slightly denoting the radius by 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{split}F\left(\xi,r,\mu\right)=\  & r\left(\mu-\frac{1}{\mu}\right)\sqrt{\left(x-\frac{r^{2}}{\xi}\right)^{2}+y^{2}}+\left(\frac{r^{2}}{\xi}-\xi\right)\sqrt{\left(x-\frac{\xi}{\mu^{2}}\right)^{2}+y^{2}}\\
 & +\left(\frac{\xi}{\mu}-\frac{\mu r^{2}}{\xi}\right)\sqrt{(x-\xi)^{2}+y^{2}}
\end{split}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

